# Example .ccrignore file.
#
# Copy this to .ccrignore in any project workspace to filter paths between
# the host and the container. ccr-fuse reads this at container start.
#
# Syntax: gitignore-style globs (one pattern per line).
#   *           any sequence of chars except '/'
#   **          any number of path components (zero or more)
#   ?           a single char except '/'
#   [abc]       character class
#   /pattern    leading slash anchors the pattern to the workspace root
#   pattern/    trailing slash restricts the pattern to directories
#   pattern     unanchored (no leading slash) matches at any depth
#
# Limitations:
#   * No negation (`!pattern`). Lines starting with `!` are skipped with a warning.
#   * Lines starting with `#` are comments. Inline `#` is NOT treated as a comment
#     (matches gitignore behavior).
#   * Path traversal patterns (`..`) are rejected.
#
# Semantics for every matched path:
#   * Host's matching file/dir is INVISIBLE inside the container.
#     stat returns ENOENT until the container creates something there.
#   * Container creates/writes/deletes are stored in a container-local
#     overlay (/var/lib/ccr/overlay) — they NEVER touch the host filesystem.
#   * Removing the container wipes the overlay; the host content is unaffected.
#
# Two typical use cases:
#   1. Secrets the container should not see (.env*, credentials, ssh keys).
#   2. Build artifacts whose architecture differs from the host (node_modules,
#      .venv, target, etc.) — the container builds its own copy.

# Secrets / private files (unanchored: at any depth)
.env.local
.env.production
.env.*.local
.aws/credentials
.ssh/id_rsa
.ssh/id_ed25519

# Build artifacts that should live only in the container
node_modules
.venv
target
.next
dist
__pycache__
*.pyc

# Local logs (any depth)
*.log

# A specific root-anchored example: hides /secret at root but NOT a/secret
# /secret

# A specific dir-anchored example: build/ at any depth, only directories
# build/
